## Theming

All of these UI elements are customizable using `plain CSS` as well but the main properties like the color, border radius, etc... are themable through your theme configuration like so:

1. Create a `themeUi.config.ts` file into your `.sugar` root package folder
2. Override the theme UI configurations like so:

```js
export default {
    button: {
        defaultColor: 'accent',
        defaultStyle: 'outline',
        depth: 0
        // etc...
    },
    avatar: {
        borderWidth: '4px',
        depth: 20
        // etc...
    }
    // etc...
}
```

## Available properties

Each UI elements have some common properties like `defaultColor` and some proper ones.
To see exactly what are these properties, check out the [configuration explorer](/doc/config/explorer).

Globally, here's the properties you can expect to be used on the most components:

- `paddingInline`: Specify the inline padding. Default: `1.5`
- `paddingBlock`: Specify the block padding. Default: `0.75`
- `borderRadius`: Specify the border radius. Default: `1`
- `borderWidth`: Specify the border width. Default: `theme.border.width.default`
- `transition`: Specify the transition to use across the UI. Default: `theme.transition.fast`
- `outline`: Specify if you want to use the outline or not across the UI. Default: `theme.ui.outline.active`
- `defaultLnf`: Specigy the default look and feel to use across the UI. Default: 'solid'
- `depth`: Specify the depth you want across your UI. Default: `theme.depth.default`
- `spacing`: Specify the default spacing to use across the UI. Default: `theme.space.30`
- `rhythmVertical.marginBottom`: Specigy the margin bottom to use in your `s-rhythm:vertical` scopes. Default: `60`

## Do not repeat ourselves

In order to keep all of these configurations clean and easy to override, make sure to use some references at place of static values when possible like so:

```js
export default function(api) {
    return {
        default: {
            depth: 30
            // etc...
        },
        button: {
            depth: api.theme.ui.default.depth
            // etc...
        }
        // etc...
    }
}
```

> Note that if you don't specify the `depth` property in the above example, it will automatically fallback to the `default.depth` value if it exists.

